  "prompt": "Phrases: Where did the term \"phoning it in\" come from, and how did it come to mean someone not trying hard enough?",
  "response": "The phrase \"phoning it in\" originated in the entertainment industry, particularly in acting and performance, and gradually spread to other professional contexts. Here's a breakdown of its origins and evolution:\n\n1. Theatrical/Performance Origins:\n- In the early-to-mid 20th century, actors would sometimes literally phone in their performance if they were unable or unwilling to be physically present.\n- This could mean reading lines over the telephone or recording a performance remotely.\n\n2. Metaphorical Meaning:\n- Over time, the phrase evolved to mean performing a task with minimal effort or enthusiasm\n- It suggests doing the bare minimum required, without genuine engagement or passion\n\n3. Probable First Usage:\n- The metaphorical usage likely emerged in the 1940s or 1950s, coinciding with the widespread adoption of telephones\n- It first gained traction in entertainment and performance circles\n\n4. Spread to Broader Usage:\n- By the 1960s and 1970s, the phrase had expanded to describe lackluster performance in various professional settings\n- It became a commonly understood idiom for doing something without real commitment or energy\n\nThe term essentially implies that someone is so disengaged that they might as well be completing a task from a distance, without personal investment.",
